                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13228" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Thu, 12 May 2005 06:47:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In general, multiple kinds of advices should work. Please try to provide a minimal test case, so that we can reproduce the issue!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juegren&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13233" author="alexguev" created="Thu, 12 May 2005 11:38:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;you&apos;ll find an eclipse project with the test cases in this zip file. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;please accept my apologies for not having submitted the test cases when I submitted the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13318" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 20 May 2005 10:51:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I see what you are referring to, Alexei: implementing multiple Advice interfaces in the same object. This is currently indeed not supported: each advice object is just resolved to a single Interceptor adapter, matching a single Advice interface.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rod, we could consider reworking this for Spring 1.3. It&apos;s probably a too fundamental change for a 1.2.x release. I have already added a test case for such a &quot;multi advice&quot; (to AbstractAopProxyTests), commented out for the time being.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13591" author="maximdim" created="Sun, 19 Jun 2005 08:27:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think Spring could have give at least a warning (or throw exception at init time) when class implementing multiple advices are detected. Just spend hours trying to debug our advice implementation before realizing this is the bug in Spring!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
